Project: Investigate a Dataset (Medical Appointments No Shows)¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Questions
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

This project deals in the investigation of appoinment records for Brasil public hospitals. The dataset includes some attributes of patients like,the patient age,gender, etc. The analysis of this project is based on the ivestigation of factors affecting patients attendance to their appointments.

Questions¶

  1. What is the age distribution for patients who showed up and patients who didn't by their genders?
  2. What is the gender distribution for patients who showed up and patients who didn't?
  3. Does Neighbourhood affect patients?
  4. What factors are important to know in order to predict if a patient will show up for their scheduled appointment?
  5. What days are being scheduled the most?
  6. Does age affect the number of attendance?

From the overview;

  1. The data has no null values(NaNs).
  2. The data has no duplicated rows.
  3. The Scheduled_Day and Appointment_Day are in string format instead of date and time format
  4. The data has a age that is less than one(1) in the description.

Cleaning Process Overview¶

  • Some headers had wrong spelling so I had to correct them.

  • This data included no null values(NaN) which did't need me to fill any row or column.

  • Two columns from the dataset was dropped which are the PatientID and AppointmentID.

  • New columns were one is to know the scheduled for the week and the other created to categorize the patient different ages.

  • The Scheduled_Day and Appointment_Day colums were converted to datetime function.

    In [242]:
    # A function to help visualize the number of occurrences of a category
def count_plot(df,xvar):
    sns.countplot(data=df,x=xvar)
    plt.title(f"Distribution of {xvar}".title(), weight ="bold")
    plt.xlabel(xvar.title(), weight = "bold")
    plt.ylabel("Frequency", weight = "bold")
    
# A function to help plot pie chart
def pie(x,labels):
    data[x].value_counts().plot(kind="pie", autopct="%1.2f%%", explode = [0,0.1], labels = labels)
    plt.title(f"Distribution of {x}".title(), weight ="bold")
    
# Knowing the percentage difference
def percent_diff(a,b):
    a=a 
    b=b
    c=a + b
    d = a/c *100
    e = b/c *100
    print(f"The percentage difference of the distribution are {round(d)}% and {round(e)}%")

    An Overview;¶

  • Gender: The percentage of show up and no show in male and female are the same.

  • Scholarship:Seems that people with scholarship have a little bit of higher percentage than those who don't show up.The proportion of people with scholarship who show up for their appointment are higher than those who don't.

  • Hypertension: The proportion of people without hypertension show up for their appointment more than people who have hypertension.

  • Diabetes:The percentage difference for diabetes is little.It shows that people without diabetes show up more than people who have diabetes.

  • Alcoholism: There seems to be an equal percentage distribution between those who show up for their appointment and those who don't.

  • Handicap: There are different percenttage changes between the four handicap categories, and category 4 tends to show up more than other, while category one shows up the least and the have higher number of people who don't turn up for thei appointment.

  • SMS_received: People who receive SMS show up more for their appointment and they have less people who don't show up for their apponitment compared to people who don't receive SMS.

    Conclusions¶

    The dataset had some wrong spellings in the column header, I corrected them and also drop some rows and some unwanted columns which were not needed for my analysis, I also compared the variables in the dataset using the "No_show" column as my dependent variable and here are my findings;

  • Popular neighborhood like JARDIM CAMBURI have more patients attending their appointment. This could be due to the service quality being provide by the hospitals in the neighborhood or sercurity reasons.This shows that neighborhood plays a role with patients meeting up with their appointments.

  • Scheduling days are mostly on Tuesdays and Wednesdays. There are no appointments or schedules for Saturdays or Sundays.

  • The age between 0 and 60 have higher attendance to their schedule.Most of the patients are infants and young children. From the data, patients between the age 0 to 40 have higher records of being registered for the welfare program.

  • Men have lower scholarships compared to women,but for every age category it seems that men show up more for their appointments than females especially from the ages from 20 years and above.

  • Most of the patients are not alcoholics.

  • Most of the patients are not diabetes but more than alcoholics. There are for handicap categories with most of the people not being handicapted. Most patients do not have hypertension diagnosed.

  • Out of 71831 appointments made by females, 14588 patients didn't attend. Out of 38685 appointments made by males, 7723 patients didn't attend. There is a 30% ratio difference between male and female The percentage change of male and female are slightly little, this proves that the high ratio of females doesn't affect the show up/no show up.

  • On average, 80% of patients attend their medical appointments in Bazil, and JARDIM CAMBURI is the most popular neighborhood where most appointments are attended. Most of the time, appointments are possible to be scheduled in the next 0 to 18 days and be arranged on weekdays.

  • In the analysis of current dataset, the factors which are the Gender, SMS, day of week and Scholarship have not demonstrated important influence on whether the patient will attend an appoitment or not. However, the patients are more willing to go to the appointment in hospitals which are in a populated area.

  • To help increase the show-up rate, some things should be acted upon:

  • 1.The shedule should also be spread out to saturday and Sunday, it maybe that the patients are busy during work days to show up.

  • 2. Neighborhood sseem to be playing a role with high show up for their appointments, it could be that the hospital maybe far
  • from the patient which causes less turn out for their appointments, so paitents should be giving the choice to pick a hospital close to their neighborhood.

  • 3.Granting and trying to encourage more males to register for the welfare program.

    • Limitations¶

    This dataset was useful to perform some ceratin extent, the data showed the various categories of illness, those that are on scholarship, their different ages, but didn't provide why the patients didn't show up to their appointment. The data wasn't categorised whether the appointment was an emergency or if it was a normal random check up, if this was stated we could have know why patients do show up or not, we would have had a better insights to thier reasons.
